snippet.textDisplay:
I did towing and recovery for a little while, and my most-used "non standard" equipment was definitely a snatch block. It opens up so many options. Not only letting you pull harder than your winch could normally do, but pulling from a direction you wouldn't be able to. There are some really neat tricks for a snatch block.


It always impressed me as being one of those tools whose usefulness was basically only limited by how clever you are... and how many you have on hand.

How do you turn 8,000 lbs of pulling force into 16,000? Snatch block!!


How do you pull a car that's stuck in park out of a parking space in a supermarket so you can turn it and load it onto a flat bed? Snatch block!!

How do you haul an 80,000 lb truck out of a ditch and back onto solid ground? Snatch blocks!!

snippet.textDisplay:
Leverage is king! I suppose another way to relate to a snatch block is the a breaker bar on a driveshaft nut. The end you apply force to vs the end applying your mechanically enhanced force to the nut.

Another and maybe marginally less obvious example are the cogs on a bicycle, especially on a mountain bike where climbing ability is needed. The smaller front cog and the larger rear cog give that mechanical advantage.

Both examples work the same as your initial multiple pulley examples where the rate of movement appears faster at the point where you're bearing against vs where the end result of your effort is displayed. Or maybe not, I might be barking up the wrong tree!

Anyway, thanks for yet another informative and interesting video!

snippet.textDisplay: Fun fact: at 5:24 the reason the block bends that way is because friction in the bearings of the pulley cause more tension in the right side of the rope than the left side of the rope. Equal tension in the rope is only true if there's no friction.
snippet.textOriginal: Fun fact: at 5:24 the reason the block bends that way is because friction in the bearings of the pulley cause more tension in the right side of the rope than the left side of the rope. Equal tension in the rope is only true if there's no friction.

snippet.textDisplay: Near the beginning I feel the focus on tension is misleading. Pulleys work like gears, ie by taking the work you put into moving your hands a distance d, and using that work to move a load only a distance 0.5d (or whatever ratio). It basically allows you to spread out your work so that your power output can be half as much for twice as long. I don't think tension really adds much to understanding this, particularly because the rope slides. It is not the same as having two people pull on fixed ropes.
